fr.apteryx.imageio.dicom
Class DicomWriter

Object
  ImageWriter
      DicomWriter
All Implemented Interfaces:
ImageTranscoder
public class DicomWriter
extends ImageWriter

The Dicom encoder.

Instances of DicomWriter are created using DicomWriterSpi.

Possible outputs are :

  • ImageOutputStream
    • for writing part 10 dicom files. If a FileImageOutputStream is supplied, beware to ensure that the underlying file does not exist or is empty, else the DicomWriter could write the DICOM data at the begining of the file, leaving the end as is, which will result in an unreadable DICOM file.
  • StorageSCU or PeerAE
    • for writing to a remote Storage SCP.
  • QueryRetrieveSCP.Operation
    • for responding to a Retrieval request.

Image metadata are not used.

If the format of the image(s) cannot be encoded as a DICOM object (e.g. the sample size is not 8 bits nor 16 bits), an exception is thrown during the write operation.

The written DICOM object belongs to the SOP class specified in the stream metadata. If no stream metadata is supplied or if the supplied stream metadata does not specify the SOP class nor the modality, the writer creates an object of a Secondary Capture or a Ultrasound SOP class depending on the format of the image(s).

If the chosen SOP class is one of the known SOP class, the writer will add any attribute that is missing according to the DICOM standard in order to obtain a conform instance of the SOP class. If the SOP class is not known by the writer, it is the responsability of the user to specify all mandatory attributes in the stream meta data.

Known SOP class are :

If the stream metadata contains an attribute that is not a standard DICOM 2004 attribute, the write operation will fail. In order to be able to write DICOM object with non-standard attribute, all non-standard attributes must be registered using Dictionary.learn.

When writing a sequence, the writing only begins when endSequence is called.

Arbitrary DICOM objects containing no images can be written using the write method and passing null for the image argument. The object to be written is defined by the DicomMetadata argument that should have been created with a valid SOP class and all necessary attributes as specified by the standard.

setRawMode

public void setRawMode(boolean b)
If set to true, all attributes values are expected to be byte[] (except sequences that are Vector of DataSet as in normal mode, and encapsulated pixel data that are byte[][]), and are writted as is. This mode is really useful only when writing back a DICOM object read with raw mode. Default is false.

convertStreamMetadata

public IIOMetadata convertStreamMetadata(IIOMetadata inData,
                                         ImageWriteParam param)
Converts a stream metadata to a Dicom metadata.

If inData is a DicomMetadata, returns a new DicomMetadata with exactly the same SOP class, SOP instance and data elements. Only The PixelData and group length elements are not copied.

Else, if inData is not a DicomMetadata, but supports the standard metadata, a new DicomMetadata is returned with some elements initialized as specified in DicomMetadata.mergeTree.

Else returns null.

setTransferSyntaxes

public void setTransferSyntaxes(String[] ts)
Sets the preferred transfer syntaxes used when writing to an ImageOutputStream (usualy to a DICOM file). Transfer syntaxes are specified by an array of UID strings, in decreasing order of preference. The transfer syntax actually used when writing an object is the first preferred syntax supported by the plugin and suitable for the object being written (The JPEG baseline transfer syntax will for instance not be suitable for objects with 12-bit pixel data).

An exception is thrown if the object cannot be encoded using any of the specified syntaxes (DicomException with code string ApplicationError).

To ensure that any DICOM object could be written, at least one of the following, always suitable, uncompressed transfer syntaxes must be specified:

  • UID.ExplicitLittleEndianTS
  • UID.ExplicitBigEndianTS
  • UID.ImplicitLittleEndianTS

By default, the list of preferred transfer syntaxes contains the single UID UID.ExplicitLittleEndianTS.

If null or an empty array is specified, the default list is restored.

This list of transfer syntaxes is not used for exchanging objects with the DICOM network service classes (Query/Retrieve and Storage).

setJPEGQuality

public void setJPEGQuality(float f)
Sets the quality setting when encoding the pixel data in lossy JPEG. The quality index ranges from 0.0 (worst) to 1.0 (best). The default value is 0.75.
